title: For Sale:  Forehand & Wadsworth .32 Hammerless Top-Break Revolver - Antique for Display or Restoration
postcontent:
This is a non-functioning antique revolver!

Forehand & Wadsworth .32 (S&W Black Powder-Only) Hammerless Top-Break Revolver

This revolver was made sometime between 1888 and 1890. The model was introduced in 1888, the company name changed sometime in 1890 to "Forehand Arms Co." after which the brand marking on the firearms changed to match. This allows for narrowing down the manufacture date to a short period. 
The matching "1926" stamping viewable on both the cylinder and bottom of the frame/handle of this revolver is the serial number, not a manufacturing date, for those curious. And here again, the S/N is a fairly low number.

As-is this gun would make a nice display piece or wall hanger. It's got the surface wear to show it was a well used gun in its' day. This is a steel gun with nickel plate finnish and an after-market stained wood hand grip of unknown age and origin. All of the rusty areas of the gun are purely from the nickel having been worn off from handling over the last one hundred and twenty-five years.

Worth Noting:
- This is a non-functioning revolver!
- If in working condition, which it isn't, this would only fire gun powder based .32 cartridges. The "grain" combustible in modern ammunition creates a great deal more pressure than gun powder and could damage the revolver and cause injury to the user.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Pre World War 1 British Enfiield Bayonet, No Import Marks, $250 OBO
postcontent:
I would like to sell my pre World War 1 Enfield Bayonet. I believe this bayonet to be an early example of a P14 bayonet, which means that it would also fit the American P17 and all models of trench shotgun from that era. The bayonet is in very good condition, as it still exhibits much of the original bluing, has the original grips and all original hardware. It has not been refinished or cleaned up, and has not been sharpened. The bayonet has the Broad Arrow Marking (British Manufacture), Crown over 33 over Large "A" (acceptance), and 1913 over 10-16 over Large "W" (manufacture date). See pictures for condition and proof marks. I am not an expert on this item, so if you happen to know more than me please feel free to share. I personally imported this bayonet, hand carried back from the middle east. More pictures on request, I am selling the other two bayonets separately. 

I am asking $200 or best reasonable offer, I have seen them go for a lot more in similar shape. I will accept any reasonable cash offer, the worst I will say is no.

postcontent:
Ruger PC4 40 S&W Police Carbine & Pistol Combo

PC4 Carbine and P94 Pistol with interchangeable magazines

Includes:

6 Original Ruger 20 Rd Mags

The PC4 Carbine:
MSRP: $749
The PC4 (.40 S&W) are patterned after the highly successful Ruger 10/22 carbine. The Carbine is intended as a shoulder weapon for police use, although it is available for sale to civilians as well. The intent is that an officer will carry a Ruger P Series pistol as a sidearm, and keep a Carbine available (for example, in his/her patrol vehicle) as a shoulder weapon if needed. Since the carbine has a 16-inch (410 mm) barrel, it provides more power with the same ammunition used by the 4-inch (100 mm) barreled pistol (see internal ballistics). The carbine also provides additional accuracy and range over the pistol.

The Carbine has some unique design features. The action is a simple blowback design, which requires a fairly massive bolt to handle the pressure of 9mm and .40 S&W. To prevent the gun from being too unbalanced by the large bolt, the bolt consists of two parts; the main body of the bolt is fairly light and located in the receiver, while the other part is just a weight located under the forend of the carbine. These two parts are held together by strong, rigid steel bars. The combined mass serves to hold the breech safely closed during firing, while keeping the center of gravity forward, so the gun handles well. Another unique feature is the bolt lock. Since blowback guns of these calibers require heavy bolts, the inertia of dropping the gun can cause the bolt to come partially open, rendering the gun unfirable until the bolt is manually closed all the way. To prevent this, the Carbine uses a lock that locks the bolt securely closed so that a fall will not dislodge it. A slight pressure on the trigger or on the bolt handle, however, will disengage the bolt so that it can move for firing or clearing the action.

The P94 Pistol:
The Ruger P94 Series is a Double Action and Single Action pistol that shoots .40 S&W ammunition.

Standard Capacity: 10 rounds 
Sights: Fixed front and rear 
Finish: Metal frame
MSRP:$649

This case is molded from ultra-high density molecular weight polyethylene (the material specified by the U.S. military for cases and containers) and was designed to carry four rifles with SKB's trademarked "bunk-bed" padding and divider protection system.
